            "ppo": "2/5 - Core PPO structure is present (GAE loop, ratio+clipped objective, minibatches, advantage normalization), but there are major correctness/robustness issues: code is incomplete (clip_grad_norm_ line truncated; no optimizer.step() shown), old_logprobs stored from unclipped pre-tanh Normal while actions passed to evaluate are clipped (log-prob mismatch), actions sampled from Normal then clamped without tanh-squash correction, returns/GAE uses mixed Python lists vs tensors and uses 'done' from last env step when bootstrapping which can be inconsistent across buffer boundaries, and no device management. Likely trains poorly or breaks.",
            "a3c": "3/5 - Implements shared global model with share_memory(), SharedAdam with shared state, per-worker local rollout with n-step bootstrapped returns, computes actor/critic losses and pushes grads to global then syncs local. However it is not true asynchronous advantage actor-critic in several ways: uses evaluate_action on raw/clipped actions with the same clamping/log-prob mismatch as PPO, no per-worker seeding, gradient sharing logic is fragile (skips setting grad if global_param.grad already exists; relies on _grad assignment), and code shown is incomplete at end of a3c_train (global_episode initialization truncated), so may not run as-is.",
            "eng": "2/5 - ActorCritic has reasonable MLPs and action scaling, but forward() is unimplemented, orthogonal init helper mostly unused, and the Gaussian policy is incorrect for bounded actions (clamp without log-prob correction). Extensive CPU numpy conversions (logprobs/value to numpy), no device handling, incomplete files (PPO/a3c cut off), and some hardcoded hyperparameters (GAE lambda=0.95 not configurable). Overall not clean/reliable."
